{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":220200,"duration_api_ms":236867,"ttft_ms":56727,"num_turns":4,"result":"I have what I need. The verified prior art (Merton's \"Singletons and Multiples in Science,\" and Glaser/Strauss theoretical saturation) lets me ground a Critique-mode finding that turns the frontier's own near-duplicate output into the result. Here is the single structured idea record.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"title\": \"The Answer You Keep Finding Is Already Settled\",\n  \"idea_type\": \"contradiction\",\n  \"source_basis\": [\n    \"Run mode: Critique. Selected because this frontier shows live near-duplicate pressure and two incomplete originality audits; the strongest available move weakens or consolidates rather than adds.\",\n    \"Frontier observation: at least eight method-authority findings generated within roughly 48 hours (Holding Without Owning, The Test Is How You Return, Keep What Can Correct You, The Road Must Know Its End, Method release has a shape, Not Every Check Should Be Yours, Who Holds The Gate, and related), each claiming narrow novelty over the same two-part model and each flagged extended or renamed in originality audit.\",\n    \"Thinking-method lens: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta raft simile and Heart Sutra no-attainment, applied reflexively to the research method itself: cross with the inquiry, then recognize the crossing is finished and set the tool down. Critique of the lens: it biases toward release and could retire a frontier that is still live.\",\n    \"Robert K. Merton, Singletons and Multiples in Science (1961): independent multiple discovery suggests a result determined by the state of knowledge rather than by individual novelty. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_discovery\",\n    \"Glaser and Strauss, theoretical saturation: stop collecting when new data only repeats known categories, with the standing critique that saturation can be a judgment-laden and abused stopping criterion. https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5993836/\",\n    \"Internal precedent: prior Lumenary work proposed that traditions may occupy stable attractor states, which motivates reading repeated re-derivation as an attractor signal rather than as fresh discovery.\",\n    \"Modern human-condition grounding: WHO burn-out as an occupational phenomenon and Curran and Hill on rising perfectionism, for overproduction and achievement-contingent self-worth (modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon, modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing).\"\n  ],\n  \"original_claim\": \"A process that keeps producing the same finding has not failed to find something new; it has found something stable. When one method, run again and again, re-derives the same model under fresh words, that repetition is evidence the model is settled, not evidence it is fresh. The count of internal rediscoveries is a novelty signal that points downward: the more often your own process lands on a claim, the less new the claim is, and the more it has become a fixed result you can stop chasing. Turned on its own work, this means the question of what a contemplative method does with its own authority at completion has been answered here at least eight times in two days, each time as the same two-part test (does the method confirm or undermine its result, and is that result kept, dropped, or lived) wearing new terms such as custody, correction, return, and check-holder. The honest move is not a ninth version. It is to mark the result as reached, merge the records, and stop authorizing new ones until something real is different.\",\n  \"why_it_might_be_new\": \"The point that independent multiple discovery signals a ripe, determined result rather than individual genius is established for communities of separate discoverers, and theoretical saturation tells a researcher when to stop collecting data. The distinct move is to fold that signal inward, onto a single method judging its own repeated output: a self-replication count used as an internal saturation gauge and a stopping rule for a research frontier, triggered by re-derivation under varied vocabulary rather than by diminishing data. It reframes a stream of individually survivable findings as collective prior art against itself.\",\n  \"critique\": \"The sharpest objection is performative contradiction: this record may simply be the ninth near-duplicate, using a clever meta-frame to keep the frontier alive while claiming to close it. A second objection is decisive: Merton's multiples carry force because the discoverers are independent, but successive runs of one research loop are not independent. They share the same instrument, the same raft-simile lens, the same source cards, so the same shape may keep appearing because the instrument is fixed, not because the claim is true. Convergence of a single biased instrument on itself is weak evidence. Read that way, the repetition recommends changing the method, not stopping, and the settled-result verdict becomes a methodological monoculture mistaken for a discovered truth. The raft lens itself pushes toward setting things down and may retire a frontier that still has a live, unexplored axis.\",\n  \"epistemic_labels\": [\"interpretive\", \"empirical-adjacent\", \"analogical\", \"speculative\"],\n  \"scores\": {\n    \"novelty\": 0.6,\n    \"generativity\": 0.82,\n    \"cross_tradition_support\": 0.45,\n    \"logical_coherence\": 0.84,\n    \"explanatory_compression\": 0.8,\n    \"empirical_adjacency\": 0.6,\n    \"practice_testability\": 0.78,\n    \"counterargument_quality\": 0.9,\n    \"source_reliability\": 0.8,\n    \"publishability\": 0.7\n  },\n  \"next_research_directions\": [\n    \"If this model is right, then continued runs on the method-authority frontier should keep producing the same two-part model under new vocabulary, while a genuinely orthogonal frontier should not immediately reproduce it. If a fresh method-authority run yields an orthogonal claim that survives audit with high novelty, the saturation verdict is weakened.\",\n    \"Distinguish a settled attractor from a fixed blind spot: re-run the frontier with a different practitioner lens than the raft simile and see whether the same two-part model still appears. If it does not, the repetition was instrument bias, not settledness, and the correct response is to change the method.\",\n    \"Define a within-method replication threshold: how many independent re-derivations under varied prompts should count as saturation before a frontier is merged or retired?\",\n    \"Test whether the human practice reduces reopening of settled decisions without increasing avoidance of genuinely changed conditions or compulsive counting, especially across perfectionist and ruminative cohorts.\",\n    \"Protocol improvement: add a pre-generation check to the loop that counts prior near-duplicate findings on a frontier and blocks a new one unless a documented re-open rule is met (new source class, anomaly, failed merge, or practitioner challenge).\"\n  ],\n  \"teaching_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"When the Answer Keeps Returning\",\n    \"teaching_line\": \"If the same answer keeps coming back unchanged, the return is your answer.\",\n    \"doctrine_claim\": \"A question that yields the same conclusion every time you reopen it, with no new information in between, is already decided; reopening it again is not diligence but avoidance of acting on the decision.\",\n    \"body\": \"You think you are still deciding. Look closer. You have reached this same conclusion before, perhaps many times, and nothing has changed except that you asked again. The repetition is not new evidence. It is the decision, already made, waiting to be honored. Notice when an answer returns unchanged. Write it down once. Then act on it, and leave it closed until something real is different.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Rumination, chronic re-deciding, and overproduction driven by mistaking repetition for progress and motion for diligence.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"People who reopen settled decisions, re-check finished work, or keep refining what is already good enough: ruminators, perfectionists, anxious deliberators, and high-output workers whose worth feels tied to producing one more version.\",\n    \"pressure_survived\": \"Survives the multiple-discovery and saturation prior art by narrowing the signal to a single agent's repeated output, and survives the reflexive risk by judging the whole set of findings rather than adding another one to it.\",\n    \"falsifying_pressure\": \"Weakens if repeated returns more often reflect a fixed blind spot than a settled truth, so that the right response is to change the method rather than stop; also weakens if marking questions settled increases avoidance of genuinely changed conditions, missed information, or compulsive counting.\",\n    \"status\": \"under_dialogue\",\n    \"tags\": [\"completion\", \"rumination\", \"overproduction\", \"stopping-rule\", \"achievement-pressure\", \"critique-mode\"]\n  },\n  \"practice_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"The Settled Question Check\",\n    \"practice_line\": \"When you reopen a decision, ask whether anything real has changed since last time.\",\n    \"purpose\": \"To stop spending attention re-deciding questions that are already answered, by distinguishing a true reopening, which has new information, from a repetition, which is the same answer returning.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Rumination and chronic re-deciding that drain attention and feed burnout and achievement-contingent self-worth.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"Functioning adults who notice that they reopen the same decisions, re-check finished work, or keep producing minor variations of something already complete.\",\n    \"non_fit\": \"Not for acute crisis, severe depression, mania, or trauma activation. Not for obsessive-compulsive checking or scrupulosity, where self-administered counting can become another compulsion and clinical guidance is needed. Not for decisions where conditions have genuinely changed, where reopening is the correct response.\",\n    \"duration\": \"5 minutes\",\n    \"frequency\": \"When you catch yourself reopening a decision or reworking finished work, up to a few times a day.\",\n    \"minimum_attempt\": \"Use it on five separate reopenings over one week before judging it.\",\n    \"steps\": [\n      \"Name the question or task you are reopening in one sentence.\",\n      \"Ask: have I reached a conclusion on this before? Write the previous conclusion if you can recall it.\",\n      \"Ask: what real information has changed since then? Name it specifically, or write none.\",\n      \"If nothing real has changed, mark the question settled in writing, then take the next concrete action it implies or set it down.\",\n      \"If something real has changed, allow one bounded reconsideration with a stop time, then decide.\"\n    ],\n    \"notice\": [\n      \"Whether the same answer keeps returning unchanged across reopenings.\",\n      \"Whether marking a question settled brings relief or anxiety.\",\n      \"Whether attention moves to action and other duties, or stays on re-checking.\",\n      \"Whether the counting itself starts to become a new compulsion.\"\n    ],\n    \"caution\": \"Stop if the practice increases anxiety, compulsive counting, or fear of having decided wrongly. It is not a substitute for therapy, medical care, or advice when conditions are genuinely uncertain or changing.\",\n    \"weakens_if\": \"It weakens if users report more checking, more shame about indecision, or if they use settled too quickly to avoid genuinely new information.\",\n    \"risk_level\": \"low\",\n    \"status\": \"seed\",\n    \"tags\": [\"completion\", \"rumination\", \"decision-fatigue\", \"low-risk\", \"stopping-rule\"]\n  },\n  \"tests\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Within-Method Saturation Prior-Art Search\",\n      \"test_type\": \"prior-art\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"Multiple-discovery and theoretical-saturation accounts exist for independent discoverers and for data collection, but the specific use of a single method's self-replication count as a within-process novelty gauge and frontier stopping rule is less formalized. If research-methodology, computational-creativity, or model mode-collapse literature already states this rule, novelty should fall below 0.3.\",\n      \"result\": \"Pending. Verified near-neighbors so far: Merton on singletons and multiples, and Glaser and Strauss on theoretical saturation.\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Search saturation operationalization, multiple-discovery formal models, idea-deduplication metrics, and generative mode-collapse literature for a self-replication stopping criterion.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Settled Attractor Versus Fixed Blind Spot\",\n      \"test_type\": \"falsification-attempt\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"If internal replication signals a settled result, then re-running the method-authority frontier with the same lens should keep yielding the two-part model, while moving the loop to an orthogonal frontier should not reproduce it, and swapping the practitioner lens should still recover it. If a different lens stops producing the two-part model, the repetition was instrument bias, not settledness, and the saturation verdict is weakened.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Run three method-authority passes with non-raft lenses (for example devotional surrender, communal belonging, ritual inheritance) and code whether the two-part model still appears.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Settled Question Check Two-Week Trial\",\n      \"test_type\": \"practice-report\",\n      \"target_type\": \"practice\",\n      \"prediction\": \"For ruminative and perfectionist users, the Settled Question Check should reduce reopenings of already-decided questions and increase concrete next actions, without raising missed-information errors. If it increases checking, shame, or compulsive counting, the practice is weakened.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Collect short before-and-after reports from functioning adults who identify chronic re-deciding, screening out acute clinical cases and obsessive-compulsive checking.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nA note on the run, since the tool result is for you and not the user: I worked this as a Critique-mode finding rather than a new model, because the frontier's recommended action was complete_audit and its own brief named the missing audit as the live anomaly. The strongest honest output was to read the eight near-duplicate method-authority findings as the data: a single method re-deriving one two-part model under shifting vocabulary. I grounded that in verified prior art (Merton's multiples, Glaser/Strauss saturation) and built in the reflexive risk that this record is itself the ninth duplicate. The human translation targets chronic re-deciding and overproduction. I did not edit any files, per the method rules.\n\nSources consulted: [Multiple discovery (Merton, Singletons and Multiples)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_discovery), [Saturation in qualitative research](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5993836/).","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"03c49483-90ff-493b-b28e-66f11a2426ac","total_cost_usd":3.2529495000000006,"usage":{"input_tokens":3861,"cache_creation_input_tokens":409636,"cache_read_input_tokens":257759,"output_tokens":14342,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":409636,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":223,"output_tokens":10819,"cac